[3] Cholera - Sudan (Central Darfur State)
Date: Wed 14 Feb 2018
Source: Radio Daganga [edited]
https://reliefweb.int/report/sudan/death-toll-mounts-central-darfur-watery-diarrhoea-outbreak


In Nierteti in Central Darfur, the death toll from acute watery diarrhea, suspected of being cholera, has amounted to 9, while the infection cases have risen to more than 100.

Yesterday, [Tue 13 Feb 2018], activists in voluntary work reported to Radio Dabanga from Nierteti that 4 people died of the disease while being transported from neighboring villages to the hospital. Up to 5 more deaths were reported from Nierteti the previous day [Mon 12 Feb 2018]. An activist from the hospital told Radio Dabanga that the medical isolation center allocated to receive the cases was full, while others are still searching for a place. He said that the isolation center has about 65 suspected cases of cholera.

A total of 2 people died from similar symptoms of acute watery diarrhea or cholera in the last week [week of Sun 4 Feb 2018]. Nierteti Hospital's designated isolation ward received a number of patients during the weekend, volunteers in the hospital told Radio Dabanga. 15 cases of cholera or diarrhea arrived from the villages of Ketzuela, Kurna, Mara and Kutrem, bringing the total number of cases in the hospital to 53 on [Mon 12 Feb 2018].

September 2017 was the last time that Nierteti Hospital was treating more than 10 cases of cholera - most of them arrived from the camps for displaced people - at a time when the spread of the epidemic in Sudan seemed to subside. A slight increase in cases was reported during the last week of 2017 and the 1st week of 2018, however: 46 and 30 new cases respectively were registered in eastern Sudan.

--
